'''Andrew Stuart Murray McCall''' (born 10 June 1964), usually known as '''Stuart McCall''', is a former Scottish [[association football|footballer]] who played in [[midfielder|central midfield]]. He is now a football [[coach (sports)|manager]], in charge of [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]].

He started his professional career with Bradford City, where he made his senior debut in 1982. He played six seasons at [[Valley Parade]], during which time he won the [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] championship, a title which was overshadowed by the [[Bradford fire|Bradford fire disaster]] when 56 people died and in which his father [[Andy McCall (footballer born 1925)|Andy]] was injured. After missing out on promotion in [[1987-88 in English football|1987&ndash;88]] he moved to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], for whom he scored twice but finished on the losing side in the [[1989 FA Cup Final]]. In 1991 he moved to [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], with whom he spent seven seasons and won six [[Scottish Premier League|league]] titles, three [[Scottish Cup]]s and two [[Scottish League Cup]]s. He returned to [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] as captain to take them into the [[Premier League|top division]] of English football for the first time in 77 years. After four seasons he moved to [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], where he retired as a player in 2005. McCall also won 40 [[cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and scored one goal in the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]] in Italy. He played in two [[UEFA European Football Championship|European Championships]] but his international career ended after he was left out of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] squad.

He was part of the coaching staff during his second spell at Bradford City, briefly serving as caretaker/player manager in 2000. He continued his coaching at Sheffield United and was assistant manager to [[Neil Warnock]] until May 2007, when he returned to Bradford City for a third time, this time as manager on 1 June 2007.

==Early life==
Stuart McCall was born on 10 June 1964 in [[Leeds]], England, to Scottish parents [[Andy McCall (footballer born 1925)|Andy]], a former professional footballer, and Jean McCall.<ref name="autobio9">{{cite book
|last=McCall
|first=Stuart
|title=The Real McCall
|publisher=Mainstream
|year=1998
|pages=p.&nbsp;9
|isbn=1-84018-078-1}}</ref> He was the couple's third child after Leslie and Janette, who were 20 and 15 respectively when Stuart was born.<ref name="autobio9"/> The family home was just round the corner from [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]]'s [[Elland Road]] ground where McCall would spend many Saturday afternoons watching United, dreaming of following his father and playing for Leeds, even after the family moved to [[Wortley, West Yorkshire|Wortley]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;9&ndash;10}}</ref><ref name="leeds">{{cite news
|first=Phil
|last=Shaw
|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/why-leeds-no-longer-have-place-in-mccalls-affections-599719.html
|title=Why Leeds no longer have place in McCall's affections
|accessdate=2007-12-28
|date=[[2003-03-07]]
|publisher=The Independent}}</ref> McCall played football for Upper Wortley Primary School and Thornhill Middle School, even scoring a winning goal for the latter in a cup final when he came on as a substitute with his arm in a sling.<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;10&ndash;11}}</ref> McCall also played [[table tennis]] as a schoolboy but excelled at football, captaining the Leeds under-11 boys team and playing for other Leeds representative sides.<ref name="autobio11-12">{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;11&ndash;12}}</ref> McCall's parents split and he made up for his size when he moved to one of Leeds' toughest estates and played for pub sides by the age of 14.<ref name="autobio11-12"/> He moved schools to Harrington High and also played for local young sides Pudsey Juniors, Holbeck and later [[Farsley Celtic A.F.C.|Farsley Celtic]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;14&ndash;16}}</ref> McCall thought he had missed his chance of playing professionally after a string of other players were signed by professional clubs, until Farsley played [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]'s junior side in a friendly and he impressed coach [[Bryan Edwards (footballer)|Bryan Edwards]] enough to be asked for a trial.<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=p.&nbsp;16}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Bradford City===
McCall came through City's youth system after he was signed by [[George Mulhall]] in 1980 from Farsley Celtic at the age of 16,<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1430229.0.cook_unearthed_city_treasure_mccall.php
|title=Cook Unearthed City Treasure McCall
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2000-05-28]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref><ref name="markham">{{cite book
|last=Markham
|first=David
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|publisher=Breedon Books Sport
|year=2007
|pages=p.&nbsp;115
|isbn=978-1-85983-572-2}}</ref> before becoming an apprentice in June 1981.<ref name ="markham"/><ref name="frost">{{cite book
|last=Frost
|first=Terry
|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903&ndash;1988
|publisher=Breedon Books Sport
|year=1988
|pages=p.&nbsp;116
|isbn=0907969380}}</ref> Mulhall's successor, [[Roy McFarland]] gave McCall his debut at [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] on 28 August 1982&mdash;the opening day of the [[1982-83 in English football|1982&ndash;83]] season&mdash;when he deputised for [[Ces Podd]] at [[defender (football)#Full back|right back]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=Dewhirst
|first=John
|title=City Memories &ndash; An Illustrated Record of Bradford City A.F.C.
|publisher=True North Book
|year=1998
|isbn=1 900 463 57 1}}</ref> He had played just six league games by 29 January 1983 when he made the first of 134 consecutive league appearances, all in midfield under new manager [[Trevor Cherry]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=Frost
|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903&ndash;1988
|pages=pp.&nbsp;306&ndash;313, p377}}</ref> City finished 12th in [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] that season.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Frost
|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903&ndash;1988
|pages=p.&nbsp;306}}</ref> The [[1983-84 in English football|following]] season City struggled to make up for the absence of [[Bobby Campbell (Northern Irish footballer)|Bobby Campbell]], who had left to join [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], and won just one of their first fifteen games,<ref name="markham p29">{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;29}}</ref> until Cherry bought Campbell back from Derby, and City won a record ten consecutive games on their way to a seventh place finish.<ref name="markham p29"/>

During the summer of 1984, Cherry made the two key signings of [[Defender (football)|central defender]] [[Dave Evans (footballer)|Dave Evans]] and [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]] [[John Hendrie]] to build on the previous season's high finish.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;81}}</ref> McCall was an integral part of the team as City won the Division Three championship in [[1984-85 in English football|1984&ndash;85]], during which he scored eight goals as one of two ever-present players.<ref name="markham"/> The title was assured in the penultimate game when McCall scored the second goal in a 2&ndash;0 victory over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=Frost
|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903&ndash;1988
|pages=p.&nbsp;37}}</ref><ref>{{cite book
|last=Frost
|title=Bradford City A Complete Record 1903&ndash;1988
|pages=p.&nbsp;310}}</ref> The league title was paraded before the final game of the season on 11 May 1985 at home to [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]. However, the club's title was overshadowed when 56 people died in the [[Bradford City disaster]] when the [[Valley Parade]] ground's main stand caught fire after 40 minutes of play, during which McCall's father, who was with other family members, was badly injured.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Richard
|last=Sutcliffe
|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/features/The-horror-a-city-can.1022622.jp
|title=The horror a city can never forget
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2005-05-11]]
|publisher=Yorkshire Post}}</ref> After the fire, McCall, still in his kit, spent several hours driving from the ground to his sister's house, then to [[Bradford Royal Infirmary]] and [[Pinderfields General Hospital|Pinderfields Hospital]] trying to find his father.<ref name="autobio tragedy">{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;42&ndash;47}}</ref> His father had suffered severe burns and needed skin grafts on his hands and head and was in hospital for several weeks.<ref name="autobio tragedy"/>

For the following 19 months, the club played games away from Valley Parade. Cherry and the players became a close-knit team, attending funerals of the victims and other engagements in the months that followed, and the club's 13th place finish in [[Football League Second Division|Division Two]] in [[1985-86 in English football|1985&ndash;86]] was hailed a major achievement.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;35}}</ref> During Bradford's time away from Valley Parade, McCall also turned his back on Leeds United, the team he had supported as a child, after their fans set fire to a chip van at [[Odsal Stadium]].<ref name="leeds"/> McCall became club captain in November 1986, aged just 21, after [[Peter Jackson (footballer born 1961)|Peter Jackson]] moved to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref name="frost"/> Under Cherry's replacement, [[Terry Dolan (footballer)|Terry Dolan]], the club held off any relegation threats to finish tenth in [[1986-87 in English football|1986&ndash;87]]. Like Jackson, McCall and Hendrie were both keen to move to a [[Football League First Division|Division One]] club, but they agreed in 1987 to stay for one final season.<ref name="markham"/>

Dolan brought in [[Paul Tomlinson]], [[Brian Mitchell (footballer)|Brian Mitchell]] and [[Lee Sinnott]] in a bid to help McCall and Hendrie realise their dreams with City.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;41}}</ref> They mounted a promotion challenge in [[1987-88 in English football|1987&ndash;88]] and were top for much of the season until they faltered in the New Year. When promotion was missed initially by one point on the last day of the season after a 3&ndash;2 defeat against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] and then through [[Football League Championship play-offs|play-off]] defeat to [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], McCall left the club, signing for [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] for [[pound sterling|<U+00A3>]]850,000 in June 1988.<ref name="frost"/> He had played 238 league games for the club, scoring 37 goals, and in total played 285 games, scoring 46 goals. McCall was later outspoken in his autobiography, ''The Real McCall'', about City's failure to strengthen the side in order to secure promotion.<ref name="payment">{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1998/6/22/174067.html
|title=Book row: McCall fumes over Tordoff's 'cheap' payment
|accessdate=2007-12-30
|date=[[1998-06-22]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref>

{{Cquotetxt|I thought about transfer deadline day and Tordoff saying we should sell before buying. One or two new faces would have taken us over the finishing line, I was sure of it, and it nagged away. It wasn't about gambling, it was about lack of ambition.|Stuart McCall|''The Real McCall''<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|pages=p.&nbsp;65}}</ref>}}

His departure was soured when he was forced to go to [[the Football League]] with a [[Professional Footballers' Association]] representative to win <U+00A3>8,327.15 of an unpaid signing-on fee.<ref name="payment"/><ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|pages=pp.&nbsp;67&ndash;68}}</ref>

===Everton===
McCall joined Everton at a time when its former triumphant side of the mid 1980s had broken up, following the ban on English sides competing in Europe, which marked the start of a period of underachievement at [[Goodison Park]].<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/history/kendall-s-heroes.html
|title=History 1981&ndash;2006
|accessdate=2007-12-28
|publisher=Everton Official Website}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2000/4/14/154405.html
|title=City v Everton: Connections
|accessdate=2007-12-28
|date=[[2000-04-14]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> His Everton debut came in a 4&ndash;0 victory over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 27 August 1988 against his former teammate Hendrie, who was making his debut for Newcastle.<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=p.&nbsp;70}}</ref> McCall also returned to [[Valley Parade]] for a [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] tie, but his Everton side were knocked out by Bradford 3&ndash;1 on 14 December 1988.<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;70&ndash;71}}</ref> He started 29 league games in [[1988-89 in English football|1988&ndash;89]] as well as another four substitute appearances. He was also a substitute in the [[1989 FA Cup Final]] when he scored Everton's equaliser in the [[Merseyside derby]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] to take the game into extra-time. He scored another equaliser during extra-time, but Liverpool's own substitute [[Ian Rush]] also scored two to secure a 3&ndash;2 victory for Liverpool.<ref name="telegraph">{{cite news
|first=William
|last=Johnson
|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2003/01/09/sfnshe09.xml
|title=McCall calls the shots in tireless show
|date=[[2003-01-08]]
|accessdate=2008-01-04
|publisher=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>

McCall made a second appearance in an Everton shirt at Valley Parade, when he was invited by former teammate [[Mark Ellis (footballer born 1962)|Mark Ellis]] to bring a side for his testimonial. In three seasons at Everton, McCall played 103 league games as well as earned his first [[cap (sport)|cap]]s with [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] but he failed to lift any trophies as the club finished eighth, sixth and ninth in the league.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.toffeeweb.com/history/records/league-record.asp
|title=Everton League Record
|accessdate=2008-03-20
|publisher=Toffee Web}}</ref>

===Rangers===
In 1991, [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] paid <U+00A3>1.2 million for McCall.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.bradfordcityfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/BantamsGreats/0,,10266~119234,00.html
|title=Stuart McCall Bantams Greats
|accessdate=2007-12-27
|publisher=Bradford City Official Website}}</ref> Rangers had just won their third successive [[Scottish Football League Premier Division|Scottish Premier Division]] title. Under manager [[Walter Smith (footballer)|Walter Smith]], McCall ended up playing in the final six of the club's nine successive Scottish league titles that firmly established them as Scotland's top club side after several years of being matched and often overtaken by [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] and [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. In his first season at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]], Rangers won the league and cup double, before they achieved greater success in [[1992-93 in Scottish football|1992&ndash;93]], winning both cups 2&ndash;1 against Aberdeen and coming nine points ahead of Aberdeen in the league.<ref name="rangers history">{{cite web
|url=http://www.rangers.premiumtv.co.uk/page/HistoryDetail/0,,5~471,00.html
|title=1997 Nine in a row
|accessdate=2008-03-18
|publisher=Rangers official website}}</ref> McCall also had European success that season when the Glasgow club narrowly missed out on an appearance in the [[UEFA Champions League 1992-93|UEFA Champions League 1992&ndash;93]] final, coming second in the semi-final group stage to eventual winners [[Olympique de Marseille]].<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.uefa.com/competitions/UCL/history/Season=1992/intro.html
|title=French first for Marseille
|accessdate=2007-12-17
|date=[[2006-01-01]]
|publisher=UEFA}}</ref> In [[1993-94 in Scottish football|1993&ndash;94]], Rangers added another [[Scottish League Cup]] title along with the league championship, but lost 1&ndash;0 in the final of the [[Scottish Cup 1993-94|Scottish Cup]] to [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]. The following season saw Rangers win the league by their greatest margin as they finished 15 points ahead of [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]], but they failed to reach the final of either domestic cup. Although their winning margin was reduced to four points, from city rivals [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], in [[1995-96 in Scottish football|1995&ndash;96]], Rangers' points tally of 87 was a record-high total. McCall played in his fourth Scottish Cup final as Rangers defeated [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] 5&ndash;1. Rangers again pushed Celtic into second place in [[1996-97 in Scottish football|1996&ndash;97]] and defeated Hearts 4&ndash;3 in the Scottish League Cup. But with the club chasing an unprecedented 10th straight title in [[1997-98 in Scottish football|1997&ndash;98]] they had to settle for the runners-up position, with Celtic winning the league by just two points on the final day of the season. McCall was substituted in the Scottish Cup final as Rangers went the season without picking up a single title for the first season in McCall's time at the club.<ref name="rangers history"/>

In February 2008, McCall became the 71st inductee into the Rangers hall of fame. McCall's former teammate and Rangers assistant manager [[Ally McCoist]] presented him with the award.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.telegraphandargus.co.uk/display.var.2070846.0.my_shock_at_gazzas_sad_demise.php
|title='My shock at Gazza's sad demise'
|date=[[2008-02-25]]
|accessdate=2008-02-25
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus
|first=Simon
|last=Parker}}</ref>

===Back to Bradford City===
McCall still had one year left on his Rangers contract in 1998, but much of the team that [[Walter Smith (footballer)|Walter Smith]] had built had left and McCall was allowed to leave on a free transfer as long as he joined an English club.<ref name="markham"/> [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] were both interested in signing McCall, but he rejoined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] as club captain.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thisisbradford.co.uk/1998/6/3/174600.html
|title=City was perfect chance: McCall
|accessdate=2007-12-28
|date=[[1998-06-03]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Rookie manager [[Paul Jewell]] put together a squad to battle for promotion, adding other new signings, including central midfield partner [[Gareth Whalley]] and [[striker]] [[Lee Mills]], who went on to be club's top goal-scorer.<ref name="markhamjewell">{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;99}}</ref> The season started off slowly with just one win from the first seven games, but by the latter half of the season, City were vying with [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for the second promotion spot behind runaway leaders [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. [[Loan (football)|Loan]] signing [[Lee Sharpe]] and [[Dean Windass]] were added to the ranks and City had the chance to seal promotion in their penultimate game against relegation-threatened [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]]. The game finished as a 0&ndash;0 draw, with McCall heading over the goal in the final minutes, taking the promotion bid to the final game of the season.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Richard
|last=Sutcliffe
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/5/13/163161.html
|title=Bantams Special: Goal-by-goal guide to the winning season
|accessdate=2007-12-05
|date=[[1999-05-13]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Days later he was named the club's player of the year.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/5/4/163536.html
|title=McCall proves he's still a first-class act
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[1999-05-04]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> A 3&ndash;2 victory over [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] at [[Molineux stadium|Molineux]] on 9 May 1999 ensured promotion to the [[Premier League]] and denied Ipswich Town&mdash;the team that had thwarted McCall and Bradford 11 years before.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1999/5/10/163253.html
|title=Bantams:Revenge is so sweet
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[1999-05-10]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Following the game, the players were celebrating with fans at the club's ground, when McCall fell off a car after drinking for more than five hours after the end of the game.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Windass
|first=Dean
|title=From Gipsyville to the Premiership
|publisher=Great Northern
|year=2007
|pages=p.&nbsp;125
|isbn=978-1-905080-29-8}}</ref>

Bradford were expected to struggle in their first season in the top flight for 77 years.<ref name="markhamjewell"/> Jewell signed [[David Wetherall]], [[Dean Saunders]] and [[Neil Redfearn]], all experienced top flight performers, but City were in the bottom four teams for most of the season. It was Bradford's home form&mdash;they earned 26 of their 36 points at Valley Parade&mdash;that was key to City avoiding relegation, which was narrowly averted by two points after a 1&ndash;0 final day victory over [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in [[1999-2000 in English football|1999&ndash;2000]].<ref>{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;201}}</ref> When Jewell left only days after the season ended, McCall was appointed assistant manager to [[Chris Hutchings]],<ref name="assistant">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/819450.stm
|title=McCall steps up, Scales eyes Ipswich
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2000-07-04]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> and subsequently served as caretaker manager for two games when Hutchings was sacked after just 12 games of the [[2000-01 in English football|2000&ndash;01]] league season.<ref name="hutchings">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/1009904.stm
|title=Bradford sack Hutchings
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2000-11-06]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> City were relegated with just 26 points. During a 6&ndash;1 defeat to [[West Yorkshire]] rivals [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] in the penultimate game, McCall and team-mate [[Andy Myers]] fought on the pitch.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/1328731.stm
|title=Bradford dust-up goes unpunished
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2001-05-13]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

McCall stayed on for one more season before he was released by then manager [[Nicky Law (footballer born 1961)|Nicky Law]] in May 2002, shortly before the club went into [[administration (insolvency)|administration]] for the first time after finishing 15th in [[Football League First Division|Division One]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/1921054.stm
|title=Bantams let McCall go
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2002-04-10]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> His playing career at Bradford City had looked uncertain in December 2001 before Law arrived, when previous manager [[Jim Jefferies]] had left McCall out of the side in a 3&ndash;1 defeat at [[Manchester City]] following a training ground dispute.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/1715361.stm
|title=Jefferies denies McCall rift
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2001-12-17]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/1719659.stm
|title=McCall's days numbered
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2001-12-19]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> However, it was Jefferies who lost out in the dispute when he resigned his post a week later after summit talks with chairman [[Geoffrey Richmond]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2001/12/27/132030.html
|title=Richmond will bide time
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2001-12-27]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> In April 2002, McCall's [[testimonial match]] against Rangers attracted a crowd of more than 21,000 to [[Valley Parade]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2002/4/29/126959.html
|title=McCall pays special tribute to City's 'wonderful fans'
|accessdate=2007-12-27
|date=[[2002-04-29]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Two years later, he played one more time in City colours in a Save Our City appeal match organised by Bradford's evening newspaper, the ''[[Bradford Telegraph and Argus|Telegraph & Argus]]'', to raise funds for the club, who were now in administration for a second time.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/5/20/100532.html
|title=Stars come out to save City
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2004-05-20]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/3513575.stm
|title=Bantams in administration
|date=[[2004-02-27]]
|accessdate=2008-02-03
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

===Sheffield United===
On 2 July 2002 McCall joined [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], where he played an integral part in their first-team side, despite being 38, and also coached the reserves to the league title.<ref name="blades">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/2086451.stm
|title=McCall signs for Blades
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2002-07-02]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He played 71 league games over the next two seasons, and scored twice, including a winner against former side Bradford.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/3113652.stm
|title=Bradford 1-2 Sheff Utd
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2003-09-27]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was in the side that reached the [[Football League First Division|Division One]] play-off final in 2003 as well as the semi-finals of both cup competitions that year.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.sufc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/FactsFigures/0,,10418~1081180,00.html
|title=A year by year history
|accessdate=2008-03-18
|publisher=Sheffield United official website}}</ref> However he and Dean Windass, who was also now at Sheffield United, were both left out of the play-off final, as United lost 3&ndash;0 to Wolverhampton Wanderers.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Windass
|title=From Gipsyville to the Premiership
|pages=p.&nbsp;119}}</ref> McCall played just two [[Carling Cup]] games in the [[2004-05 in English football|2004&ndash;05]] season, and retired just a few weeks before his 41st birthday.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/3729224.stm
|title=McCall set to end career
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2004-10-09]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

==International career==
McCall was picked for [[England national under-21 football team|England]] and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland]] under 21 sides on the same day in 1984,<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;32&ndash;33}}</ref> and chose to play for England in a game against [[Turkey national under-21 football team|Turkey]]. However, he was only picked as a substitute and the referee blew the final whistle with McCall waiting to come on.<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|page=pp.&nbsp;35&ndash;36}}</ref> This meant he was still eligible for both England and Scotland, and McCall eventually switched allegiances to the latter, for whom he qualified through his father, making his debut in March 1988, ironically against England.<ref name="frost"/>

He went on to be [[cap (sport)|capped]] by the [[Scotland national football team|Scottish senior]] team and made his debut on 28 March 1990 in a 1&ndash;0 friendly victory over [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref name="caps">{{cite web
|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/scotland/players/stuartm.mccall.html
|title=Stuart McCall &ndash; Scotland Football Record
|accessdate=2007-12-27
|publisher=Londonhearts.com}}</ref> He played in five friendlies in 1990 which earned him a call up to the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|Italia 90 World Cup]] squad. He played in all three of Scotland's World Cup games. They lost their first game 1&ndash;0 to [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], before McCall scored what would be his only international goal against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] in a 2&ndash;1 victory.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=76/results/matches/match=127/report.html
|title=Costa Rica &ndash; Scotland
|accessdate=2007-12-27
|publisher=FIFA.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=76/results/matches/match=348/report.html
|title=Sweden &ndash; Scotland
|accessdate=2007-12-27
|publisher=FIFA.com}}</ref> However, Scotland failed to qualify for the knock-out stage when they were defeated 1&ndash;0 by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=76/results/matches/match=74/report.html
|title=Brazil &ndash; Scotland
|accessdate=2007-12-27
|publisher=FIFA.com}}</ref>

McCall represented Scotland at the European Championships in [[UEFA Euro 1992|1992]], when they again failed to go beyond the group stage after defeats to [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and [[Germany national football team|Germany]], and in [[UEFA Euro 96|1996]] when they were edged out in the first round by Netherlands.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/player_details.cfm?playerid=14370&squadid=1
|title=Stuart McCall &ndash; A Squad
|accessdate=2008-03-18
|publisher=Scottish Football Association}}</ref> Scotland failed to qualify for the World Cup in [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]]. McCall played just two qualifying games for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] and his last cap came in a friendly against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] on 25 March 1998, as he was overlooked for the final squad for the finals in France along with team-mate [[Ally McCoist]].<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/1998/6/8/174489.html
|title=McCall's World Cup blast
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[1998-06-08]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> He was capped a total of 40 times for Scotland, scoring one goal.<ref name="caps"/> McCall's caps included 11 while at Everton and 29 during his career with Rangers.<ref name="caps"/>

==Coaching and management career==
===Early coaching career===
In July 2000, McCall accepted his first coaching role, when he was appointed assistant manager to [[Chris Hutchings]] at Bradford City, after Hutchings was promoted from the role to replace [[Paul Jewell]] as City manager.<ref name="assistant"/> Just four months later, Hutchings was sacked, and McCall was appointed as caretaker/player manager.<ref name="hutchings"/> His first game as manager was against his former team [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], who were managed by his former manager Walter Smith, but ended with a 1&ndash;0 defeat.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/1018397.stm
|title=Everton sink Bradford
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2000-11-11]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was in charge for one more game, which also ended in defeat, until [[Jim Jefferies]] was appointed the new manager. Jefferies brought with him his own assistant Billy Brown, and McCall was appointed first-team coach.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/1027129.stm
|title=Jefferies is new Bradford manager
|accessdate=2007-12-17
|date=[[2000-11-20]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

After leaving Bradford City, he joined Sheffield United, where he also took up a coaching role.<ref name="blades"/> When he retired in 2004, he remained at Sheffield United as assistant to [[Neil Warnock]].<ref name="blades post">{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/6664639.stm
|title=McCall misses out on Blades post
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2007-05-17]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Working alongside Warnock and learning the managerial ropes from him,<ref>{{cite news
|first=Rob
|last=Stewart
|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2004/03/06/sfnshe06.xml
|title=McCall yearns for a final farewell
|accessdate=2008-01-04
|date=[[2004-03-05]]
|publisher=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|first=Louise
|last=Taylor
|url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,,1163565,00.html
|title=McCall enjoys the age of colour
|accessdate=2008-01-14
|date=[[2004-03-06]]
|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> he helped mastermind Sheffield's promotion to the Premier League in 2006.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/4912522.stm
|title=Blades promoted after Leeds draw
|accessdate=2007-12-17
|date=[[2006-04-15]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> United were relegated to the Championship on the final day of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season and Warnock resigned three days later.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6627849.stm
|title=Sheff Utd 1-2 Wigan
|accessdate=2007-12-17
|date=[[2007-05-14]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/6659513.stm
|title=Warnock resigns after Blades manager
|accessdate=2007-12-17
|date=[[2007-05-16]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> McCall had already decided that the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season would be his last as assistant manager,<ref name="markham"/> and when he was overlooked as a successor to the United manager's position, in favour of [[Bryan Robson]], he decided to leave after five years with the club.<ref name="blades post"/>

===Return to Bradford City===
McCall admitted in his autobiography, ''The Real McCall'', he wanted to manage Bradford.

{{Cquotetxt|One day in the distant future I would love to manage Bradford.|Stuart McCall|''The Real McCall''<ref>{{cite book
|last=McCall
|title=The Real McCall
|pages=p.&nbsp;184}}</ref>}}

He had been linked with the manager's position at Bradford City on numerous previous occasions,<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2000/6/20/152419.html
|title=Is it time for boss McCall?
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2000-06-20]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/1013556.stm
|title=Evans favourite for Bradford post
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2000-11-08]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_utd/3264473.stm
|title=McCall rules out Bradford switch
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2003-11-12]]
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> and after [[Colin Todd]] was sacked on 12 February 2007,<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/6354497.stm
|title=Bradford part company with Todd
|date=[[2007-02-12]]
|accessdate=2008-03-17
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> City chairman [[Julian Rhodes]] made McCall his number one target to take over in the summer.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1206514.0.mccall_is_no1_target.php
|title=McCall Is No1 Target
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2007-02-21]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> Club captain [[David Wetherall]] temporarily took over and was later announced as caretaker manager for the rest of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/6444657.stm
|title=Wetherall to stay on as caretaker
|date=[[2007-03-13]]
|accessdate=2008-03-17
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 18 May 2007 it was announced McCall would become full-time manager of the club where he started his career, and on 1 June 2007 he assumed the position.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1407886.0.mccall_says_yes_to_city.php
|title=McCall Says Yes To City
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2007-05-18]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> In less than seven years since McCall's first two-game reign, serious financial problems had driven the club to the verge of closure, and although they survived the threat of oblivion, they were unable to avoid a terrible on-the-pitch decline, which continued after the financial nightmare had been relieved.<ref>{{cite book
|last=Markham
|title=The legends of Bradford City
|pages=p.&nbsp;161}}</ref> On McCall's return to [[Valley Parade]], the Bantams had just been relegated to [[Football League Two|League Two]]&mdash;meaning that they would be playing in the bottom division for the first time in 25 years.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1362773.0.woeful_city_relegated.php
|title=Woeful City relegated
|accessdate=2007-12-17
|date=[[2007-04-28]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> McCall set himself a target of earning promotion back to [[Football League One|League One]] in his first season.<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1456117.0.mccall_ill_have_failed_if_we_dont_go_up.php
|title=McCall: I'll Have Failed If We Don't Go Up
|accessdate=2007-12-03
|date=[[2007-06-08]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref>

Bradford had just 13 players when McCall took over,<ref>{{cite news
|first=Dave
|last=Craven
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1446155.0.bookies_tip_city_to_bounce_back.php
|title=Bookies Tip City To Bounce Back
|accessdate=2007-12-04
|date=[[2007-06-04]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> and he made a number of summer signings including defender [[Darren Williams]], midfielders [[Kyle Nix]], [[Alex Rhodes (footballer)|Alex Rhodes]] and [[Scott Phelan]], and strikers [[Barry Conlon]], [[Guylain Ndumbu-Nsungu]] and [[Peter Thorne (footballer)|Peter Thorne]].<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1513921.0.mccall_nets_a_brace.php
|title=McCall nets a brace
|accessdate=2007-12-04
|date=[[2007-07-02]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1558878.0.dday_for_city_trialists.php
|title=D-Day for City trialists
|accessdate=2007-12-04
|date=[[2007-07-19]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1607050.0.mccall_makes_a_double_signing.php
|title=McCall makes a double signing
|accessdate=2007-12-04
|date=[[2007-08-09]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> McCall recorded his first win as a manager against [[Wrexham F.C.|Wrexham]] on 25 August 2007 after substitute [[Luke Medley]] scored a late winner,<ref>{{cite news
|first=Simon
|last=Parker
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.1644538.0.luke_whos_a_hit_with_city_fans.php
|title=Luke who's a hit with City fans!
|accessdate=2007-12-30
|date=[[2007-08-26]]
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> but despite his pre-season target his team have spent most of the season in the bottom half of the table. After going unbeaten in January, the club were still 15th in League Two, and McCall told the ''[[Bradford Telegraph & Argus|Telegraph & Argus]]'' he did not regret his pre-season target but was carried away with the euphoria at the time.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/search/display.var.2011939.0.mccall_the_big_interview.php
|title=McCall: The big interview
|date=[[2008-02-01]]
|accessdate=2008-02-03
|publisher=Telegraph & Argus
|first=Jim
|last=Greenhalf
|quote=I don't regret it because it's how I felt and how I feel because I am optimistic. You should always strive to be the best you can naturally be, if that means setting standards high. But I probably went along with the optimism, na<U+00EF>vely.
I thought I would be able to get the people I wanted to get in. Looking back I should have realised I would be coming into the unknown. I think I am confident in my ability to lead other people but I probably got carried away. I think I got caught up in all the euphoria at the time, if I am being honest.}}</ref> City's form continued to improve during the second half of the season, and McCall led his side to 10th place in League Two.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/league2.sd?seasonid=137&competitionid=4
|title=Final 2007/2008 Football League Two Table
|accessdate=2008-03-05
|publisher=Soccerbase}}</ref>

Despite City finishing outside the play-off places, they were again installed as favourites for promotion by bookmakers for the [[2008-09 in English football|2008&ndash;09]] season.<ref name="wethers">{{cite news
|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/yorkshire-soccer/BRADFORD-CITY-Wethers-targets-promotion.4282660.jp
|title=Wethers targets promotion
|date=[[2008-07-13]]
|accessdate=2008-09-15
|publisher=Yorkshire Evening Post}}</ref> McCall released 13&nbsp;players from his squad and replaced them with a number of signings with experience in a higher division, as well as [[Michael Boulding]], who was one of League Two's top goalscorers during the [[2007-08 in English football|2007&ndash;08]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/7375137.stm
|title=Bradford City release 13 players 
|date=[[2008-04-30]]
|accessdate=2008-09-15
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref name="wethers"/><ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/7525062.stm
|title=Bradford sign Boulding brothers
|date=[[2008-07-25]]
|accessdate=2008-09-15
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> McCall's side made a good start to the season, and after winning five of their opening six league games, went top of the league&mdash;the first time City had led the table in seven years.<ref>{{cite news
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/7616376.stm
|title=Boulding sets sights on promotion 
|date=[[2008-09-15]]
|accessdate=2008-09-15
|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

